TY  - JOUR
T1  - Template Use and the Effectiveness of Knowledge Transfer
AU  - Jensen, Robert J.
AU  - Szulanski, Gabriel
Y1  - 2007/08/03
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1070.0740
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1070.0740
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1716
EP  - 1730
VL  - 53
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper is a direct empirical examination of the fundamental claim that use of templates enhances the effectiveness of knowledge transfer. We explore the effect of template use through an eight-year, in-depth field investigation of Rank Xerox (now Xerox Europe). The field investigation covers three sequential transfer efforts in 15 western European countries. The investigation reveals a naturally occurring, repeated-treatment quasi experiment that allows us to test the hypothesis that the use of templates enhances the effectiveness of knowledge transfer. ?Observations? in this experiment measure the extent of adoption and performance of the practice at the recipient units. The ?treatment? is the use of a template during the transfer.
AB  - This paper is a direct empirical examination of the fundamental claim that use of templates enhances the effectiveness of knowledge transfer. We explore the effect of template use through an eight-year, in-depth field investigation of Rank Xerox (now Xerox Europe). The field investigation covers three sequential transfer efforts in 15 western European countries. The investigation reveals a naturally occurring, repeated-treatment quasi experiment that allows us to test the hypothesis that the use of templates enhances the effectiveness of knowledge transfer. ?Observations? in this experiment measure the extent of adoption and performance of the practice at the recipient units. The ?treatment? is the use of a template during the transfer.
